Thanks for this awesome new product! I'm using the following `schema.graphql` with an app I created through the CLI. 
```graphql
type Activity @model @auth(rules: [{ allow: public }]) {
  id: ID!
  slug: String!
  description: String
  periods: [ActivityPeriod] @connection(keyName: "byActivity", fields: ["id"])
}

type Period @model @auth(rules: [{ allow: public }]) {
  id: ID!
  slug: String!
  startDate: AWSDateTime!
  endDate: AWSDateTime!
  activities: [ActivityPeriod] @connection(keyName: "byPeriod", fields: ["id"])
}

type ActivityPeriod
  @model
  @key(name: "byActivity", fields: ["activityID", "periodID"])
  @key(name: "byPeriod", fields: ["periodID", "activityID"])
  @auth(rules: [{ allow: public }, { allow: public }]) {
  id: ID!
  activityID: ID!
  periodID: ID!
  activity: Activity! @connection(fields: ["activityID"])
  period: Period! @connection(fields: ["periodID"])
  available: Boolean!
}
```

The adminUI recognizes this as an m:n relationship, but doesn't show the `ActivityPeriod` model, although I'd like to be able to configure the fields for this relationship (e.q. `available: Boolean!` in this example). 

<img width="1552" alt="Screenshot of AdminUI" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9018689/101245699-deaece80-370e-11eb-9b67-4fd02d604ae7.png">

Furthermore the content tab is hanging on a loading state, not sure if that's related? 
Something I'm doing wrong, or is this kind of m:n relationships not (yet) supported?
